XVII. sed. redeo ad antiquos: sc. Pythagoreos, as distinguished from those referred to in multaque saecula postea...‚ for whom compare Zeller, Fre-Soc. Phil. 1 337, ‘The spread of Italian Pythagoream- ism was brought about by the dispersion of the Pythagoreans long after the death of the master.' For the cause of the dispersion cf. ibid. p. 357, and for the duration of the school p. 367‚ ⁴ We are expressly told that Philolaus was the first Pythagorean who published a philosophi- cal work, that before his time no Pytha- gorean writings were known, and that Pythagoras himself wrote nothing.‘ Zeller 1 313. Cicero is tracing the development of the doctrine. Pherecydes asserted it; the early Pythagoreans established it; Plato gave reasons for it. Cicero does not want to contrast early with later Pythagoreans but merely to trace the history of the doctrine.
